Are officer involved shootings increasing in Phoenix? (and other questionsâ€¦)

01 December, 2021


The behavior of police officers has been a major event in 2020. So, we might wonder whether officer involved shootings have become more common (or rare?) in Phoenix over the last few years. We can try and answer this question by examining the officer involved shootings data from the City of Phoenix open data portal. Letâ€™s get to it!


About the Data

The dataset is a CSV file containing all officer involved shooting incidents by Phoenix Police Department officers from January 1, 2017 to a week prior to the current date. Accidental discharges, discharges at animals, and discharges at objects where there was not an active threat by a subject are not included in this data set.

As of December, 2021, there were 183 crime incidents with complete data from January 2017 to within a week of the current date.


The dataset contains information about:

  • When the incident occurred (e.g.Â DATE, TIME, HOUR)

  • Where the incident occurred (e.g.Â LOCATION, PRECINCT, COUNCIL_DIST)

  • The suspect, denoted by the SP_ prefix (e.g.Â SP_RACE, SP_GENDER)

  • The officer(s) involved, deonted by the PO_ prefix (e.g.Â PO_RACE, PO_ETHNICITY)

  • And the outcome, such as the injury level (i.e.Â SP_INJURY_LEVEL) and whether there was a fatality (i.e.Â FATALITY_FLG)


Getting the data (code)

# set the url where the data are located.
url <- "https://www.phoenixopendata.com/dataset/1e472b1f-80c1-4686-b80f-e930616f8580/resource/8f8c1739-b905-407f-9eb6-6b10db55b931/download/ois.csv"

# pull in the csv file.
shooting.data <- read.csv( url, as.is = TRUE, header = TRUE )

# drop cases missing on date.
shooting.data <- na.omit( shooting.data )

# take a look at the data.
head( shooting.data )

Preprocessing the data (code)

Now that the data are in the workspace, letâ€™s clean up the dates using the strptime() and format() functions here.

# The date and time variable is a character string.
head( shooting.data$DATE )
## [1] "09-JAN-17" "09-JAN-17" "02-MAR-17" "15-MAR-17" "15-MAR-17" "23-MAR-17"
is.character( shooting.data$DATE )
## [1] TRUE
# Since the month variable is in an unusual format, we need to convert the date string to a date format code. Then pull off the month.
date.vec <- strptime( shooting.data$DATE, format="%d-%b-%y" )

# Now, let's use the format() function to create the month.
shooting.data$month  <- format( date.vec, format="%B" )


Monthly Incidents


As a first step, letâ€™s take a look at the monthly occurrence of officer involved shootings. The plot shows the monthly count of officer involved shootings from January, 2017 to December, 2021.



The plot shows several interesting patterns:

  • First, there are multiple months throughout the years in which there are no shootings.

  • Second, April 2018 and December 2020 both stick out as unusual in that there were 13 in each of these months.

  • Third, 2020 is an unusual year in terms of trends. Beginning in August, there is a consistent increase until December. There were 50 officer involved shootings in 2020. For 2017, 2018, and 2019, there were 29, 26, and 26 officer involved shootings, respectively. So, for 2020, there were nearly twice as many officer involved shootings.

  • Fourth, 2021 shows a decline in the first half.

(code)


# Create an object that is monthly counts and sorted by year. 
shootings.by.month <- 
  shooting.data %>% 
  select( YEAR, month ) %>%   
  group_by( YEAR, month ) %>% 
  summarize( counts = n() ) %>% 
  spread( YEAR, counts ) %>% 
  arrange( match( month, month.name ) ) %>% 
  select( !month )

# Replace missing values with zero.
shootings.by.month[ is.na( shootings.by.month ) == TRUE ] <- 0

# Use the ts() function to create a time series object.
monthly.shootings.by.year <- ts(
  matrix( as.matrix( shootings.by.month ), ncol = 1 ), 
  start=c( 2017, 1 ), 
  end=c( as.numeric( tail( names( crimes.by.month ), n=1 ) ), 12 ), 
  frequency=12
)

# Finally, let's take a look using ggseasonplot().
library( ggplot2 )
library( forecast )

# Now, plot it.
monthly.shootings.by.year %>% 
  ggseasonplot(
    year.labels=FALSE,
    main = "Plot of Monthly Officer Involved Shootings by Years for Phoenix" ) + 
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma) +
  theme_gray()


Suspect Characteristics


Additionally, we can examine the characteristics of the individuals who are shot. In the data, there are several variables for â€œsuspect characteristicsâ€.

There are a few interesting features of the data:

  • Of the 183 shootings, 114 were fatal, a proportion of 0.62.

  • Whites account for the majority of cases, with a proportion of 0.67.

The plot below shows the frequency distribution (i.e.Â counts) of shootings by age, outcome (where red is a fatality), and faceted by whether the suspect is White or Non-White.




(code)


# Create a plot with race, age, and the outcome.
ggplot(
  shooting.data %>% 
  select( SP_RACE, SP_AGE_AT_INC, FATALITY_FLG ) %>% 
  mutate( sp_wnw = ifelse( SP_RACE != "White", "Non-White", "White" ) ) %>%
  mutate( SP_AGE_AT_INC = replace( SP_AGE_AT_INC, SP_AGE_AT_INC == 120, 12 ) ) %>% 
  group_by( sp_wnw, SP_AGE_AT_INC, FATALITY_FLG ) %>% 
  summarize( counts = n() ) ) +
 geom_col( aes( SP_AGE_AT_INC, counts, fill = FATALITY_FLG ) ) +
 facet_wrap( ~sp_wnw ) +
 labs( x = "Suspect Age" ) +
 labs( fill = "Outcome of Shooting" ) +
 scale_fill_manual(values = c("#ca0222", "#02677b")) +
 labs( title = "Plot of Suspect Age, Suspect Race, and Outcome for Officer Involved Shootings in Phoenix" ) +
 theme_gray()
